The Fragility of the Flat World
The world is flat!
Columnist Thomas Friedman said this. Friedman chose this highly provocative book title for his bestseller to make people aware of the astonishing impact of technology on the world economy.
Distances are shrinking.
Geographic barriers can no longer easily provide protection.
Manufacturing workers and high-tech professionals in Europe and the United States all have to face the challenge of global competition.
When Western consumers call local companies, the employees they speak to may very well be far away in India.
Skeptics point out the limitations of Friedman's metaphor.
As someone said, the world is not flat, but "bumpy."
A topographic map of global economic activity shows peaks of prosperity and valleys of deprivation.
Not only that, distance is far from irrelevant.
Even between neighboring countries with low tariff barriers, such as Canada and the United States, domestic trade is much greater than cross-border trade.
Seattle and Vancouver are geographically close, but Vancouver's trade with the farther Toronto is much greater than its trade with the nearby Seattle.
Despite such criticisms, Friedman still put forward an important point.
Globalization can be defined as interdependence between different continents, its history as long as human history, witnessing migrations of races and religions, as well as the trade along the ancient Silk Road between medieval Europe and Asia.
But today's globalization is different; it develops faster and is more profound.
In 1868, after the first transatlantic telegraph cable was laid, Europe and the United States could communicate within a minute.
In 1919, economist John Maynard Keynes described a British person living in London ordering goods from around the world by telephone and then sitting at home to receive them in the afternoon.
But Keynes's British person was a special case of the wealthy.
Today, hundreds of millions of people around the world can buy goods from all over the world in their local supermarkets.
Similarly, instant global communication appeared 20 years ago, but it was beyond the reach of most people economically.
Now, almost anyone can walk into an internet café and gain access to capabilities that were once only available to governments, multinational corporations, and a small number of individuals or institutions with large budgets.
The significant decline in the costs of computation, communication, and transportation has made technology increasingly widespread.
Just ten years ago, two-thirds of internet users were concentrated in the United States.
But today, the share of internet users in the United States accounts for less than a quarter of the global total.
Knowledge is power, and today the number of people who have access to information has reached the highest level in human history.
Non-state institutions now possess capabilities that were previously only held by governments.
The status of the nation-state as a key actor in world politics will not change for now, but it must learn to share this vast stage with more participants, including institutions like the Oxford Committee for Famine Relief, celebrities like Bono, and transnational terrorist networks like Al-Qaeda.
But this process of flattening is reversible.
Similar situations have occurred before.
The world economy was highly integrated in 1914, but the level of economic interdependence among countries declined over the next 30 years.
It was not until 1970 that the global economy recovered to the level of integration it had once reached, and at that time it was still heavily constrained by the Iron Curtain.
World War I was the catalyst for this reversal, and during the two world wars and one global Cold War, people witnessed a decline in economic globalization and an increase in military globalization.
This reflected the deeper issues caused by 19th-century economic development, such as domestic inequality.
Politics failed to adapt to economic development, resulting in abnormal ideologies—fascism and communism—dominating the era. This pathological development ideology caused fragmentation within nations and around the world.
The welfare state system in the West after World War II provided a safety net for those harmed by economic changes, encouraging them to accept the benefits of international economic interdependence.
Some analysts argue that the role China plays today is very similar to that of Germany in the 20th century.
They are rising powers troubled by domestic inequality, constantly developing toward nationalism, challenging the dominant powers, and eventually triggering world wars that reverse the progress of economic globalization.
Although the economies of the United States and China are highly interdependent today, were the economies of Britain and Germany before 1914 not also highly interdependent?
But such reasoning is incomplete.
After 1900, Germany's industrial production had already surpassed that of Britain.
However, even if China maintains its current high growth rate, its economy is unlikely to catch up with the United States within at least 20 years.
The non-state and transnational forces unleashed by the spread of technology may pose a greater threat to the flat world.
On September 11, 2001, a non-state network killed more Americans in an unannounced attack than the Japanese government's Pearl Harbor attack in 1941.
I call this phenomenon the privatization of war.
If such forces acquire nuclear weapons and biological materials, the world would undergo a complete transformation.
At that time, the movement of people and goods across borders would become more difficult.
If these forces disrupt the oil exports from the Persian Gulf, which holds two-thirds of the world's oil reserves, a global economic depression similar to the 1930s could further strengthen the forces of protectionism.
Technology and policy are the two major drivers of globalization.
So far, policies have further reinforced the flattening effects of technology.
As the world's largest economic entity, the United States has taken the leading role in promoting policies to remove barriers.
But the events described above may reverse this policy.
Some critics of globalization might welcome such an outcome.
But such an outcome, as we saw after 1914, would lead to the worst situations in two areas—namely, the reversal of the trend of economic globalization that spreads technology and power, while the negative consequences of military and ecological globalization further consolidate, such as the spread of war, terrorism, climate change, and infectious diseases.
If that is the case, the flat world would become a desert.
